      "A. Lange & Söhne was founded on 7 December 1845 by Ferdinand Adolph Lange in Glashütte, in the Kingdom of Saxony. Lange did not merely start a workshop; he effectively founded the German precision-watchmaking industry, training apprentices and establishing the division-of-labor system that turned a poor mining town into a horological center. Over the following century the firm became one of the world's pre-eminent makers of precision pocket watches, prized by royalty and serious collectors.",
      'The 20th century nearly erased it. The Glashütte area was hit by an air raid on the final day of World War II in Europe (8 May 1945), and in 1948 the company was expropriated and nationalized by the East German authorities, eventually folding into the state-owned GUB (Glashütter Uhrenbetriebe). For four decades the Lange name effectively ceased to exist as an independent brand.',
      "The modern revival is one of watchmaking's great comeback stories. After German reunification, Walter Lange — great-grandson of the founder — re-registered the name and founded Lange Uhren GmbH in 1990, exactly 145 years after the original founding, in partnership with IWC's Günter Blümlein. The first modern collection launched in October 1994, led by the now-iconic Lange 1, instantly re-establishing the brand at the summit of the industry.",
      'Since 2000 Lange Uhren GmbH has been part of the Swiss Richemont Group, which secured full ownership in the early 2000s. Despite Swiss corporate ownership, the watches remain wholly designed and built in Glashütte. Today Lange is widely regarded as the only non-Swiss maker spoken of in the same breath as Patek Philippe and Vacheron Constantin, and by many enthusiasts as having the finest serially-produced movement finishing in the world.',
