      "By the 2020s Richard Mille had become shorthand for extreme wealth — a fixture on the wrists of rappers, footballers, and the global ultra-rich. It deliberately closed third-party retail in favor of its own boutiques, kept production artificially scarce against soaring demand, and rode (then partly weathered) the 2021–2022 luxury-watch bubble. The market softened in 2023–2024 and stabilized into 2025–2026, with current-production sport references holding value far better than discontinued mid-tier pieces. Audemars Piguet's ~10% stake aside, the company remains proudly independent and family-controlled.",
