      'Glashütte Original leans on 1845 in its marketing — the year Ferdinand Adolph Lange and fellow watchmakers established fine watchmaking in the Saxon town of Glashütte, later reinforced by the German School of Watchmaking (1878). That regional heritage is genuine, but the company itself is younger, and its story is inseparable from 20th-century German history.',
      "After WWII the Soviet-occupied region's watchmaking firms were expropriated and merged in 1951 into the state-owned VEB Glashütter Uhrenbetriebe (GUB), which produced watches throughout the East German (DDR) era. Following reunification, the privatized successor Glashütter Uhrenbetrieb GmbH was registered in 1990, and in 1994 entrepreneur Heinz W. Pfeifer bought the tiny ~72-employee firm and rebranded it Glashütte Original, deliberately reviving the traditional Saxon codes: the three-quarter plate, swan-neck fine adjustment, gold chatons, and the duplex-numeral Panorama Date.",
      'In 2000 the brand was acquired by the Swatch Group, which provided the capital for international expansion, a flagship boutique presence, and the resources to deepen its already-formidable vertical integration — including bringing dial production fully in-house at a dedicated facility in Pforzheim. Under Swatch ownership it developed modern movement families such as the long-power-reserve Calibre 36 (over 100 hours, with an in-house silicon balance spring) and the Calibre 39 used across much of the range.',
      "Today Glashütte Original is regarded as Germany's most vertically integrated serial manufacture and, alongside A. Lange & Söhne, one of the two pillars of high-end Saxon watchmaking. Lange chases the rarefied, hand-finished collector's summit; Glashütte Original occupies the tier just below — broader, more wearable, more automatic-heavy, and substantially more affordable — which is precisely the gap enthusiasts celebrate it for filling.",
