      "Across the 20th century IWC built its reputation on robust, legible, engineering-led watches rather than Genevan ornamentation. The Portugieser arrived in 1939, when Portuguese importers asked for a wristwatch with marine-chronometer precision, yielding the now-signature large, clean dial with railway-track minutes and feuille hands. The Big Pilot lineage and oversized navigation watches followed around 1940, establishing the cockpit-legibility DNA the brand still trades on. Post-war, IWC made its name in anti-magnetism with the Ingenieur (1955) and in diving with the Aquatimer (1967). It also became a quiet technical powerhouse: the Pellaton automatic winding system and, later, Kurt Klaus's mechanically programmed Da Vinci Perpetual Calendar (1985) showed real horological ambition.",
      "Two design landmarks define the modern brand's collectibility. In 1976 Gerald Genta penned the Ingenieur SL 'Jumbo' (ref. 1832), an integrated-bracelet luxury sports watch in the Royal Oak/Nautilus idiom; it sold poorly at the time (only around a thousand pieces) but is now coveted, and IWC has repeatedly tried to recapture it, most seriously with the 2023 Ingenieur Automatic 40. The Portofino (1984) gave IWC its clean dress-watch pillar.",
