      "The 1936 Radiomir prototype established the template: a large cushion-shaped case, wire lugs, and a dial made luminous with Radiomir, a radium-based compound Panerai had patented in 1916. In 1949 the company patented Luminor, a safer tritium-based luminescent substance, and around 1950 introduced the Luminor case with its signature crown-protecting lever bridge — the single most recognizable feature in the brand's design language. Roughly 1,600 of these military instruments were produced between the 1930s and 1990s, almost all classified and never sold to the public, which is why genuine vintage Panerais are exceedingly rare and valuable today.",
