      "For its first two decades Hublot was a respected but relatively quiet single-watch story. The transformation came in 2004 when Jean-Claude Biver, fresh from reviving Blancpain and Omega, took over as CEO and minority shareholder. In April 2005 he launched the Big Bang chronograph, a bold, oversized, multi-material sandwich-construction case that exploded into a sales phenomenon and became the brand's signature. Biver formalized the 'Art of Fusion' philosophy: combining gold, ceramic, carbon, titanium, rubber, and later more exotic materials in ways traditional Swiss houses avoided.",
      "In April 2008, LVMH acquired Hublot from Crocco, making it a sibling to TAG Heuer and Zenith in the group's watch division; Biver stayed on (later as chairman) and Ricardo Guadalupe became CEO. Under LVMH, Hublot built a true manufacture in Nyon and pushed hard on in-house R&D, launching its first in-house chronograph, the Unico, in 2009-2010, and material innovations such as scratch-resistant Magic Gold (2011, developed with EPFL) and increasingly complex full-sapphire cases.",
