      'The defining turn came in 1963. With no family heir wishing to continue, Paul-Andre Chopard sold the company to Karl Scheufele III, a German goldsmith and watchmaker from Pforzheim who wanted his own movement source. The Scheufele family has owned Chopard outright ever since, making it one of the largest still-independent, family-run watch and jewelry houses. It remains co-presided over by Karl-Friedrich Scheufele (watches) and his sister Caroline Scheufele (jewelry/Happy Diamonds).',
      "Two product moments shaped the modern brand. In 1976 designer Ronald Kurowski created Happy Diamonds, with diamonds spinning freely between two sapphire crystals — a commercial phenomenon that became Happy Sport in 1993 and remains a brand signature. Then in 1996, pushed by Karl-Friedrich Scheufele's ambition to be taken seriously by collectors, Chopard opened its own manufacture in Fleurier and launched the L.U.C line with the micro-rotor Calibre 1.96 (developed with Michel Parmigiani's input), which won Watch of the Year. The L.U.C 1860 dress watch announced that Chopard could play the haute horlogerie game.",
