      "The 1960s were Heuer's golden era under Jack Heuer, great-grandson of the founder. The Autavia (AUTomobile + AVIAtion) arrived in 1962, the angular, racing-inspired Carrera — named after the deadly Carrera Panamericana road race — in 1963, and the square, water-resistant Monaco in 1969. That same year, Heuer co-developed the Calibre 11 'Chronomatic' with Breitling, Hamilton-Büren and Dubois-Dépraz under codename 'Project 99', one of the contenders (alongside Zenith's El Primero and Seiko) for the world's first automatic chronograph. Steve McQueen wearing the blue Monaco in the 1971 film Le Mans turned the watch into a pop-culture icon.",
      "Like most Swiss makers, Heuer was battered by the 1970s–80s quartz crisis. In 1985 the Techniques d'Avant Garde (TAG) group took a majority stake, creating TAG Heuer and pivoting the brand toward sporty, accessible Swiss watches — the plastic-bezel Formula 1 became a 1980s hit. In 1999, LVMH acquired TAG Heuer for roughly CHF 1.15 billion, making it the anchor of the conglomerate's watch division.",
      "Under LVMH, TAG Heuer has pushed hard on both volume and credibility: the avant-garde belt-driven Monaco V4 concept (2004) and its 2014 tourbillon version, the Carrera Mikrograph/Pendulum experiments, the Isograph carbon hairspring, the Connected smartwatch line (now on TAG Heuer's own OS rather than Wear OS), and — most importantly for enthusiasts — the in-house Heuer 02 chronograph. As Official Timekeeper of Formula 1, the brand leans heavily into motorsport marketing while trying to shed its reputation as a discount-driven mall brand.",
