      "For decades Oris was constrained by Switzerland's protectionist Watch Statute (the so-called 'Uhrenstatut'), which limited it largely to pin-lever (cheaper) movements. The fight to overturn those restrictions became part of company lore. Then the quartz crisis of the 1970s gutted mechanical watchmaking, and in 1970 Oris was absorbed into ASUAG — the conglomerate that would later become the Swatch Group.",
      'The pivotal moment came in 1982: managing director Dr. Rolf Portmann and head of marketing Ulrich W. Herzog led a management buyout, pulling Oris back out of the conglomerate and re-establishing it as an independent company. Crucially, the newly independent Oris made a defining strategic bet — it abandoned quartz entirely and committed to purely mechanical watches in the affordable mid-price segment, adopting the now-signature red rotor as a visible mark of that mechanical identity.',
