      "The 20th century is where Tissot earned its enthusiast respect through a steady drumbeat of firsts. In 1930 it released the Antimagnetique, billed as the world's first non-magnetic wristwatch, and the same era saw the brand merge its interests with Omega to form the SSIH group. In 1953 came the Navigator, an automatic capable of showing 24 time zones, and in 1971 the Astrolon (Idea 2001), a genuinely radical mechanical movement molded largely from plastic. Tissot also leaned into unusual materials with its Rock Watch, Wood Watch, and Pearl Watch lines in the 1980s.",
      "The brand's defining technological statement arrived in 1999 with the T-Touch, a multifunction watch controlled by tapping a touch-sensitive sapphire crystal — a compass, altimeter, barometer, and thermometer on the wrist, and a legitimate piece of horological innovation that remains a Tissot signature today. Through the quartz crisis Tissot's fate became tied to the consolidation that produced SMH, and in 1998 SMH renamed itself the Swatch Group, with Tissot positioned as the group's high-volume Swiss-Made anchor.",
