    parentGroup: 'Independent (privately owned by the Steim family since 2009)',
    tagline:
      "Bauhaus on the wrist: Germany's master of minimalist design, at a price mere mortals can reach.",
    history: [
      "Junghans was founded in 1861 in Schramberg, in the eastern Black Forest, by Erhard Junghans together with his brother-in-law Jakob Zeller-Tobler. It began as a maker of clock parts and components, shifting to complete clocks and pocket watches from 1866. The firm scaled with remarkable speed: by 1903 it was the largest clock and watch manufacturer in the world, employing around 3,000 people, its eight-pointed star becoming one of Germany's most recognizable trademarks.",
      "Wristwatch production began in 1927, and Junghans supplied both military and civilian markets through the following decades. By 1956 it was the third-largest chronometer producer in the world, behind only Rolex and Omega — a high-water mark for German watchmaking. The defining creative chapter came in the 1950s and 60s through collaboration with Swiss Bauhaus-trained artist, architect and designer Max Bill, who produced the iconic Kitchen Clock with timer and a series of wristwatches whose pared-back, supremely legible dials remain the brand's commercial and aesthetic backbone today.",
      "Junghans was the official timekeeper of the 1972 Munich Summer Olympics. In the electronic era it pushed genuine innovation: the first radio-controlled table clock in the late 1980s, the first radio-controlled wristwatch (the MEGA 1) in 1990 designed by Hartmut Esslinger's Frog Design, and later solar and radio-controlled lines. Like much of the German and Swiss industry, it was battered by the quartz crisis and changed hands several times.",
      "The modern turning point came in 2009, when the entrepreneurial Steim family of Schramberg — owners of spring-maker Kern-Liebers, with watchmaking roots in the town dating to the 1880s — acquired the company and returned it to local, private, family ownership. Under the Steims, Junghans has leaned hard into its design heritage, expanding the Max Bill and Meister lines and positioning itself as Germany's accessible design house.",
    ],
    positioning:
      'Entry-to-mid-range German design brand. Sits in the roughly $900-$3,000 sweet spot, well below compatriots Glashutte Original or A. Lange & Sohne. Buyers are design-literate enthusiasts, architects, and "I want something tasteful and different from a Swiss diver" types who prize restraint, legibility, and Bauhaus pedigree over horological flexing. The Max Bill in particular is a perennial first-good-watch and design-snob favorite.',
