      "The 'Certina' brand was registered on 15 February 1924 but did not come into regular use until 1938. The defining moment in the brand's identity arrived in 1959 with the launch of the DS — 'Double Security' — concept. Engineered under Philipp Kurth, the DS system encased the movement in a shock-absorbing ring and added a reinforced caseback and improved sealing, producing watches engineered to be exceptionally rugged and water-resistant. The turtle emblem became its enduring symbol of durability.",
      "Through the 1960s and 70s Certina built a reputation in sports and tool watches: the DS PH200M diver (1967), and the Chronolympic chronographs used in sports and Olympic timekeeping. That era produced one of the brand's great stories — examples accompanied a 1970 Japanese Everest expedition, with Yuichiro Miura wearing a Chronolympic during his record ski descent. As a member of the ASUAG conglomerate, Certina was folded into the consolidated SMH group in 1983 (ASUAG + SSIH), which became the Swatch Group, where it remains today.",
      'In the modern era Certina has leaned into its archive, reissuing heritage icons like the DS PH200M (2018) and the DS-2 Chronograph, while equipping the line with Swatch Group technology — the long-reserve Powermatic 80 movement and the antimagnetic Nivachron hairspring. The result is a brand with genuine 19th-century pedigree and a real horological milestone in the DS concept, that today functions as one of the most quietly recommended value plays in Swiss mechanical watches.',
