      "Seiko's global breakthrough came as Official Timer of the 1964 Tokyo Olympics, which validated its precision on the world stage and accelerated its R&D. The defining moment arrived on 25 December 1969, when Seiko launched the Quartz-Astron, the world's first commercial quartz wristwatch (a gold-cased, 200-unit run). It triggered the 'Quartz Crisis' that nearly destroyed the Swiss mechanical industry. The same era produced the 6139 automatic chronograph, among the first self-winding chronographs in the world, cementing Seiko as a true innovator rather than a low-cost follower.",
      'Crucially, Seiko never abandoned mechanical watchmaking. It continued to develop fully in-house automatic calibers (the 7S, then hacking/hand-winding 4R, longer-reserve 6R, and hand-assembled 8L families) and, in 1999, introduced the Spring Drive: a uniquely Seiko movement powered by a mainspring but regulated electronically by a quartz oscillator, giving a true gliding seconds hand. Its dive watches, beginning with the 1965 62MAS and running through the 6309/7002, SKX, Turtle, Samurai, Sumo and Marinemaster lineages, became enthusiast legends and the foundation of a huge aftermarket modding culture.',
      "In 2017 Grand Seiko was spun out as a fully independent brand, dropping 'Seiko' from its dials to pursue the luxury segment, leaving the Seiko name focused on accessible-to-mid-tier watches under Prospex (sport/dive), Presage (mechanical dress), Seiko 5 Sports (entry automatics) and a broad quartz catalog. The corporate parent was renamed Seiko Group Corporation in 2022; Seiko Watch Corporation handles the watch brands. Today Seiko is among the most respected and ubiquitous names in horology, the value benchmark against which much of the industry is judged.",
