    tagline:
      'The plastic quartz watch that rescued Swiss watchmaking — and still outsells half the industry on charm alone.',
    history: [
      "Swatch launched on 1 March 1983 in Zurich, conceived inside ETA SA under CEO Ernst Thomke with engineers Jacques Muller and Elmar Mock, and driven commercially by Nicolas Hayek. The name is a contraction of 'second watch' — the pitch was an affordable, swappable fashion accessory rather than a once-in-a-lifetime heirloom. Its real breakthrough was construction: a sealed plastic case with the movement assembled directly into the case back, cutting the part count to roughly 51 and making a Swiss-made watch cheap enough to mass-produce with full automation.",
      "That manufacturing trick let Swiss industry fight the Japanese quartz onslaught on price and volume — the Quartz Crisis — instead of surrendering the entry segment. Swatch's profits became the financial bedrock of SMH (Société de Microélectronique et d'Horlogerie, formed from the 1983 ASUAG–SSIH merger), which was renamed The Swatch Group in 1998. The cheap plastic watch quite literally bankrolled the survival and consolidation of Omega, Longines, Rado, Tissot, Breguet, Blancpain and the rest of the group.",
      "Through the 1980s and 1990s Swatch became a genuine pop-culture and design phenomenon. Artist-collaboration models (Keith Haring, Kiki Picasso, Vivienne Westwood and many others) turned a disposable watch into a collectible; certain early and limited pieces now trade for hundreds or thousands on the secondary market, far above their original sticker. The brand's identity fused Swiss engineering with Pop-art irreverence in a way no luxury maison could replicate.",
      'In 2013 Swatch reasserted its technical credibility with Sistem51, a self-winding mechanical movement of just 51 components built on a fully automated line — a world first — with a single central screw and a ~90-hour power reserve. Then in March 2022 came the Bioceramic MoonSwatch, a roughly $260 quartz reinterpretation of the Omega Speedmaster Moonwatch. It triggered worldwide queues and scalping, sold over a million units in its first year, and reportedly lifted sales of the genuine Omega Speedmaster by around 50%. It remains the defining mass-market watch event of the decade.',
    ],
    positioning:
      'Entry-level/fashion Swiss watchmaking sold as fun, colorful, swappable accessories. The core line lives at pocket-money prices, but Swatch punches far above its weight thanks to the genuinely clever Sistem51 automatic and the cultural megaphone of the MoonSwatch. Buyers span kids and casual fashion shoppers, design-minded collectors who chase the art collaborations and limited editions, and serious enthusiasts who respect Swatch as the engine that funded the entire modern Swatch Group. It is the rare "cheap" brand that earns genuine enthusiast affection rather than dismissal.',
